  {title: "The Awards I Would Have Trophees", author: "Donnia", link: "http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/the-awards-i-would-have-trophees/", content: "<p>Le designer <a href=\"https://www.behance.net/sergiospain\">Sergio Alonso</a> (qui travaille pour Droga5 NY) et le photographe <a href=\"http://www.ericbarbero.com/\">Eric Barbero</a> ont collaboré ensemble pour une série intitulée <em>The Awards I Would Have</em>. Il s’est décerné des prix avec beaucoup d’humour et d’autodérision, qui se basent sur des habitudes quotidiennes et anecdotiques : le prix des câbles électriques les plus emmêlés derrière la télévision, de la meilleure utilisation d’un journal pour tuer des mouches, du plus long brossage de dents et bien d’autres.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/the-awards-i-would-have-trophees/awardsiwouldhave-0/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-719689\"><img src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/awardsiwouldhave-0-900x643.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"643\"></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/the-awards-i-would-have-trophees/awardsiwouldhave-1/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-719690\"><img src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/awardsiwouldhave-1-900x643.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"643\"></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/the-awards-i-would-have-trophees/awardsiwouldhave-2/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-719691\"><img src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/awardsiwouldhave-2-900x643.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"643\"></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/the-awards-i-would-have-trophees/awardsiwouldhave-3/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-719692\"><img src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/awardsiwouldhave-3-900x643.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"643\"></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/the-awards-i-would-have-trophees/awardsiwouldhave-6/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-719693\"><img src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/awardsiwouldhave-6-900x643.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"643\"></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/the-awards-i-would-have-trophees/awardsiwouldhave-7/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-719694\"><img src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/awardsiwouldhave-7-900x643.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"643\"></a></p>\n<p><em>Retouch : Roman Vychnevsky &amp; Pierre Delort.</em></p>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/the-awards-i-would-have-trophees/awardsiwouldhave-7/\"><img width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/awardsiwouldhave-7-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"awardsiwouldhave-7\"></a>\n<a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/the-awards-i-would-have-trophees/awardsiwouldhave-6/\"><img width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/awardsiwouldhave-6-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"awardsiwouldhave-6\"></a>\n<a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/the-awards-i-would-have-trophees/awardsiwouldhave-3/\"><img width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/awardsiwouldhave-3-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"awardsiwouldhave-3\"></a>\n<a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/the-awards-i-would-have-trophees/awardsiwouldhave-2/\"><img width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/awardsiwouldhave-2-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"awardsiwouldhave-2\"></a>\n<a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/the-awards-i-would-have-trophees/awardsiwouldhave-1/\"><img width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/awardsiwouldhave-1-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"awardsiwouldhave-1\"></a>\n<a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/the-awards-i-would-have-trophees/awardsiwouldhave-0/\"><img width=\"150\" height=\"150\" src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/awardsiwouldhave-0-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"awardsiwouldhave-0\"></a>\n\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/fubiz/~4/SzSGOQaY2Sk\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\" alt=\"\">", publishedDate: "2015-10-16", contentSnippet: "Le designer Sergio Alonso (qui travaille pour Droga5 NY) et le photographe Eric Barbero ont collaboré ensemble pour une série ...", feed_id: 1, categories: "[\"Design\", \"Sculpture\", \"award\", \"Droga5 NY\", \"Eric Barbero\", \"funny\", \"gold\", \"Pierre Delort\", \"Roman Vychnevsky\", \"sculpture\", \"The Awards I Would Have\", \"Trophees\"]"},
  {title: "How Do We Know What We Want: Milan Kundera on the Central Ambivalences of Life and Love", author: "Maria Popova", link: "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/brainpickings/rss/~3/g8S0jvGiNbM/", content: "<h3>“We can never know what to want, because, living only one life, we can neither compare it with our previous lives nor perfect it in our lives to come… We live everything as it comes, without warning.”</h3>\n<hr>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Unbearable-Lightness-Being-Novel/dp/0061148520/?tag=braipick-20\"><img src=\"https://i0.wp.com/www.brainpickings.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/unbearablelightnessofbeing_kundera.jpg?w=210\"></a><em>“Live as if you were living already for the second time,”</em> Viktor Frankl wrote in his <a href=\"https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/03/26/viktor-frankl-mans-search-for-meaning/\">1946 masterwork on the human search for meaning</a>, <em>“and as if you had acted the first time as wrongly as you are about to act now!”</em> And yet we only live once, with no rehearsal or reprise — a fact at once so oppressive and so full of possibility that it renders us, in the sublime words of Polish poet Wislawa Szymborska, <a href=\"https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/07/02/amanda-palmer-reads-wislawa-szymborska/\">“ill-prepared for the privilege of living.”</a> All the while, we walk forward accompanied by the specters of versions of ourselves we failed to or chose not to become. <em>“Our lived lives,”</em> wrote psychoanalyst Adam Phillips in his <a href=\"https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/08/17/missing-out-adam-phillips/\">magnificent manifesto for missing out</a>, <em>“might become a protracted mourning for, or an endless tantrum about, the lives we were unable to live. But the exemptions we suffer, whether forced or chosen, make us who we are.”</em> We perform this existential dance of yeses and nos to the siren song of one immutable question: How do we know what we want, what <em>to</em> want?</p>\n<a href=\"https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/07/07/best-illustrations-alice-in-wonderland/\"><img src=\"https://i0.wp.com/www.brainpickings.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/steadman_alice16.jpg?w=500\" width=\"600\"></a>Art by Ralph Steadman from <a href=\"https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/07/07/best-illustrations-alice-in-wonderland/\">a rare edition of <em>Alice’s Adventures in Wonderland</em></a>\n<p>Czech-French writer <strong>Milan Kundera</strong> examines our ambivalent amble through life with unparalleled grace and poetic precision in his 1984 novel <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Unbearable-Lightness-Being-Novel/dp/0061148520/?tag=braipick-20\"><strong><em>The Unbearable Lightness of Being</em></strong></a> (<a href=\"http://www.worldcat.org/title/unbearable-lightness-of-being/oclc/10072333&amp;referer=brief_results\"><em>public library</em></a>) — one of the most beloved and enduringly rewarding books of the past century.</p>\n<p>Because love heightens all of our senses and amplifies our existing preoccupations, it is perhaps in love that life’s central ambivalences grow most disorienting — something the novel’s protagonist, Tomáš, tussles with as he finds himself consumed with the idea of a lover he barely knows:</p>\n<blockquote><p>He had come to feel an inexplicable love for this all but complete stranger.</p>\n<p>[…]</p>\n<p>But was it love? … Was it simply the hysteria of a man who, aware deep down of his inaptitude for love, felt the self-deluding need to simulate it? … Looking out over the courtyard at the dirty walls, he realized he had no idea whether it was hysteria or love.</p></blockquote>\n<p>The woman eventually becomes Tomáš’s wife, which only further affirms that even the rightest choice can present itself to us shrouded in uncertainty and doubt at the outset, its rightness only crystallized in the clarity of hindsight. Kundera captures the universal predicament undergirding Tomáš’s particular perplexity:</p>\n<blockquote><p>We can never know what to want, because, living only one life, we can neither compare it with our previous lives nor perfect it in our lives to come.</p>\n<p>[…]</p>\n<p>There is no means of testing which decision is better, because there is no basis for comparison. We live everything as it comes, without warning, like an actor going on cold. And what  can life be worth if the first rehearsal for life is life itself? That is why life is always like a sketch. No, “sketch” is not quite the word, because a sketch is an outline of something, the groundwork for a picture, whereas the sketch that is our life is a sketch for nothing, an outline with no picture.</p></blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Unbearable-Lightness-Being-Novel/dp/0061148520/?tag=braipick-20\"><strong><em>The Unbearable Lightness of Being</em></strong></a>, it bears repeating, is one of the most life-magnifying books one could ever read. Complement this particular point of inflection with Donald Barthelme on <a href=\"https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/04/07/donald-barthelme-not-knowing/\">the art of not-knowing</a> and Adam Phillips on <a href=\"https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/08/17/missing-out-adam-phillips/\">the rewards of the unlived life</a>.</p>\n<hr><h3>donating = loving</h3><p>Bringing you (ad-free) Brain Pickings takes me hundreds of hours each month. If you find any joy and stimulation here, please consider becoming a Supporting Member with a recurring monthly <a href=\"https://www.brainpickings.org/donate/\">donation</a> of your choosing, between a cup of tea and a good dinner.</p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<h3>newsletter</h3>\n<p>Brain Pickings has a free weekly newsletter. It comes out on Sundays and offers the week’s most unmissable reads. Here’s <a href=\"http://us2.campaign-archive1.com/?u=13eb080d8a315477042e0d5b1&amp;id=de29ba37e7&amp;e=b2dbad0745\">what to expect</a>. Like? <a href=\"https://www.brainpickings.org/newsletter/\">Sign up.</a></p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/brainpickings/rss/~4/g8S0jvGiNbM\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\" alt=\"\">", publishedDate: "2015-10-16", contentSnippet: "\"We can never know what to want, because, living only one life, we can neither compare it with our previous lives nor perfect ...", feed_id: 3, categories: "[\"culture\", \"books\", \"love\", \"Milan Kundera\", \"philosophy\"]"},
  {title: "Community Time: What Was Your First Camera?", author: "DL Cade", link: "https://iso.500px.com/community-time-what-was-your-first-camera/", content: "<p>Most of the time, following 500px on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px\">Twitter</a>, <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/500px\">Facebook</a>, or any of the other social networks means a constant stream of beautiful photography and inspiration. Not a bad status quo. But sometimes we kick it up a notch and have a little bit of fun, too.</p>\n<p>On October 8th, we decided to make Throwback Thursday a photographic affair on Twitter, and asked you to answer the question: “What was the first camera you ever owned?”</p>\n<p><center><br>\n<blockquote lang=\"en\">\n<p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\">It&#39;s <a href=\"https://twitter.com/hashtag/ThrowbackThursday?src=hash\">#ThrowbackThursday</a>! ? What was the first <a href=\"https://twitter.com/hashtag/camera?src=hash\">#camera</a> you ever owned? <a href=\"https://t.co/OqfpUkLHVb\">https://t.co/OqfpUkLHVb</a> Pic: Maja Topcagic <a href=\"http://t.co/IAZUXCwDgI\">pic.twitter.com/IAZUXCwDgI</a></p>\n<p>— 500px (@500px) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px/status/652174291996442624\">October 8, 2015</a></p></blockquote>\n<p></p></center></p>\n<p>You guys delivered in spades!!! Some shared pictures of their first cameras, some waxed eloquent in 140 characters, some were hilariously embarrassed, and others shared touching stories about passing that same camera down to your children so they could discover photography like you did. Even our co-founder Evgeny got in on the action!</p>\n<p>Here are just a few of the tweets we got back:<br>\n<center></center></p>\n<blockquote lang=\"en\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px\">@500px</a> Can&#39;t believe I&#39;m admitting to this… My first camera: <a href=\"http://t.co/Rp1xY2p6mI\">pic.twitter.com/Rp1xY2p6mI</a></p>\n<p>— Rob Haney (@TheRobHaney) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/TheRobHaney/status/652184891455488000\">October 8, 2015</a></p></blockquote>\n<p></p>\n<blockquote lang=\"en\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px\">@500px</a> first digital camera a Minolta Dimage X now used by my daughter. <a href=\"http://t.co/y0afI0cEIO\">pic.twitter.com/y0afI0cEIO</a></p>\n<p>— Graham (@GraHodgetts) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/GraHodgetts/status/652194287740952576\">October 8, 2015</a></p></blockquote>\n<p></p>\n<blockquote lang=\"en\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px\">@500px</a> Got this from Santa in 1999. <a href=\"http://t.co/V5kfI2pvDq\">pic.twitter.com/V5kfI2pvDq</a></p>\n<p>— Niko Richard Karumaa (@RicRoughland) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/RicRoughland/status/652194490355159040\">October 8, 2015</a></p></blockquote>\n<p></p>\n<blockquote lang=\"en\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px\">@500px</a> the very first one was a 3.3MP Olympus 3040z, was saving up for more than a year for it! <a href=\"http://t.co/W1HXrNHf6Y\">http://t.co/W1HXrNHf6Y</a></p>\n<p>— Evgeny Tchebotarev (@tchebotarev) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tchebotarev/status/652176446555836416\">October 8, 2015</a></p></blockquote>\n<p></p>\n<blockquote lang=\"en\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px\">@500px</a> A kodak disc 6000. The flattest camera ever, and that fold down flap was pretty nifty. <a href=\"http://t.co/KA5CkvyP1f\">pic.twitter.com/KA5CkvyP1f</a></p>\n<p>— Melissa Camille (@MelissaCamille) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/MelissaCamille/status/652188694057644032\">October 8, 2015</a></p></blockquote>\n<p></p>\n<blockquote lang=\"en\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px\">@500px</a> My first camera was a Pentax ME Super. I was 13. Bought it with paper route money. <a href=\"http://t.co/0zEOGYFCZK\">pic.twitter.com/0zEOGYFCZK</a></p>\n<p>— Brian Dykes (@AlohaBry) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/AlohaBry/status/652198405138194432\">October 8, 2015</a></p></blockquote>\n<p></p>\n<blockquote lang=\"en\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px\">@500px</a> My very first camera that I bought myself was a Fuji Finepix 2600z, boasting 2 megapixel resolution. <a href=\"http://t.co/IQn6FIvm5t\">pic.twitter.com/IQn6FIvm5t</a></p>\n<p>— jon cruz (@cruzin510) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/cruzin510/status/652189561691377664\">October 8, 2015</a></p></blockquote>\n<p></p>\n<blockquote lang=\"en\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\">.<a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px\">@500px</a> This was my first &quot;camera&quot;, but I&#39;m pretty sure it doesn&#39;t count. <img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/72x72/1f609.png\" alt=\"😉\" style=\"height:1em;max-height:1em\"> <a href=\"http://t.co/xwdmSu3RTG\">pic.twitter.com/xwdmSu3RTG</a></p>\n<p>— Jamey M. (@JameyMPhoto) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/JameyMPhoto/status/652190816794886144\">October 8, 2015</a></p></blockquote>\n<p></p>\n<blockquote lang=\"en\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px\">@500px</a> first camera i had as a kid was a Kodak Disc camera. Top that. \n\nNow i have an Olympus OMD EM5 <a href=\"http://t.co/UUho8ydXpQ\">pic.twitter.com/UUho8ydXpQ</a></p>\n<p>— goofrider (@goofrider) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/goofrider/status/652189322116902912\">October 8, 2015</a></p></blockquote>\n<p></p>\n<blockquote lang=\"en\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px\">@500px</a> My first camera was my Father&#39;s early 1980s Pentax K1000; First digital was late 1990s Kodak DC290 <a href=\"http://t.co/KxSPU1u8Fm\">pic.twitter.com/KxSPU1u8Fm</a></p>\n<p>— Ohad Ben-Yoseph (@OhadBY) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/OhadBY/status/652256673587851266\">October 8, 2015</a></p></blockquote>\n<p></p>\n<blockquote lang=\"en\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px\">@500px</a> Built like a tank and handled like one too. <a href=\"http://t.co/EdKT5OtOlX\">pic.twitter.com/EdKT5OtOlX</a></p>\n<p>— DB (@DeeBee_UK) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/DeeBee_UK/status/652196819657707521\">October 8, 2015</a></p></blockquote>\n<p><br>\n</p>\n<p>You can check out all the responses in the Twitter thread <a href=\"https://twitter.com/500px/status/652174291996442624\"><b><u>here</u></b></a>. But why just watch the conversation when you could contribute to it! Reply to the embedded tweet at the top or add your voice to the conversation! If you don’t have a Twitter, drop a picture/link/statement in the comments below.</p>\n<p>What was your first camera? Let’s get nostalgic and start the weekend with our rose colored glasses on.</p>", publishedDate: "2015-10-16", contentSnippet: "What was your first camera? Join the conversation and start the weekend off on a nostalgic note!", feed_id: 2, categories: "[\"Headline\", \"Inspiration\", \"Stories\", \"film\", \"film is not dead\", \"film photography\", \"first\", \"first camera\", \"nostalgia\", \"rose colored glasses\", \"Twitter\"]"},
  {title: "Tiny & Mobile Minimalist Cottage", author: "Donnia", link: "http://www.fubiz.net/2015/10/16/tiny-mobile-minimalist-cottage/", content: "<p>Imaginée par l’architecte japonais Jo Nagasaka (qui travaille pour la firme <a href=\"http://schemata.jp/\">Schemata Architecture Office</a>), <em>Paco</em> est une cabane mobile blanche et paisible, construite sur le concept du cottage. Possédant un toit ouvrant, cette petite maison a tout le nécessaire pour adopter un style de vie minimaliste avec un hamac, une mini salle de bain dotée d’une douche, une pièce pour dormir et un bureau.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/en/2015/10/16/tiny-mobile-minimalist-cottage/paco_design_1/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-719478\"><img src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Paco_design_1-900x600.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"600\"></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/en/2015/10/16/tiny-mobile-minimalist-cottage/paco_design_2/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-719479\"><img src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Paco_design_2-900x600.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"600\"></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/en/2015/10/16/tiny-mobile-minimalist-cottage/paco_design_3/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-719480\"><img src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Paco_design_3-900x600.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"600\"></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/en/2015/10/16/tiny-mobile-minimalist-cottage/paco_design_4/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-719481\"><img src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Paco_design_4-900x600.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"600\"></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/en/2015/10/16/tiny-mobile-minimalist-cottage/paco_design_5/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-719482\"><img src=\"http://www.fubiz.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Paco_design_5-900x600.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"600\"></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.fubiz.net/en/2015/10/16/tiny-mobile-minimalist-cottage/paco_